SQL Practice Repository

This repository contains a **complete SQL practice set (20+ interview-level questions)** using a sample company database.

Database Name

SQL_COMPANY_DB

Tables Used :

* Departments
* Employees
* Customers
* Products
* Orders
* Sales
* MonthlySales
* SalesTeam

Concepts Practiced

✔ SELECT queries
✔ WHERE filtering
✔ JOIN (INNER, LEFT)
✔ GROUP BY & HAVING
✔ Aggregate functions
✔ Subqueries
✔ Window functions (LAG)
✔ Date functions

SQL PRACTICE QUESTIONS

1. Find duplicate customer records

```sql id="q1"
SELECT customer_name, email
FROM Customers
GROUP BY customer_name, email
HAVING COUNT(*) > 1;

🔹 2. Replace NULL salaries with 0

```sql id="q2"
UPDATE Employees
SET salary = 0
WHERE salary IS NULL;

3. Top 5 highest-paid employees

```sql id="q3"
SELECT emp_name, salary
FROM Employees
ORDER BY salary DESC
LIMIT 5;

4. Employees whose names start with 'A'

```sql id="q4"
SELECT emp_name
FROM Employees
WHERE emp_name LIKE 'A%';

5. Orders between two dates

```sql id="q5"
SELECT *
FROM Orders
WHERE order_date BETWEEN '2025-01-01' AND '2025-03-31';
🔹 6. Employee with department name

```sql id="q6"
SELECT e.emp_name, d.dept_name
FROM Employees e
LEFT JOIN Departments d
ON e.dept_id = d.dept_id;
 
7. Employees without department

```sql id="q7"
SELECT emp_name
FROM Employees
WHERE dept_id IS NULL;

8. Departments without employees

```sql id="q8"
SELECT d.dept_name, e.emp_name
FROM Departments d
LEFT JOIN Employees e
ON d.dept_id = e.dept_id;

9. Customers who did not place orders

```sql id="q9"
SELECT customer_id
FROM Customers
WHERE customer_id NOT IN (SELECT customer_id FROM Orders);

10. Customers with & without orders

```sql id="q10"
SELECT c.customer_name, o.order_id
FROM Customers c
LEFT JOIN Orders o
ON c.customer_id = o.customer_id;

11. Month-wise total sales

```sql id="q11"
SELECT MONTH(order_date) AS month,
       SUM(amount) AS total_sales
FROM Sales
GROUP BY MONTH(order_date);

12. Department-wise average salary

```sql id="q12"
SELECT dept_id, AVG(salary)
FROM Employees
GROUP BY dept_id;

13. Department with max employees

```sql id="q13"
SELECT d.dept_name, COUNT(*) AS emp_count
FROM Departments d
LEFT JOIN Employees e
ON d.dept_id = e.dept_id
GROUP BY d.dept_name
ORDER BY emp_count DESC
LIMIT 1;

14. Second highest salary

```sql id="q14"
SELECT DISTINCT salary
FROM Employees
ORDER BY salary DESC
LIMIT 1 OFFSET 1;

15. Duplicate emails

```sql id="q15"
SELECT email
FROM Customers
GROUP BY email
HAVING COUNT(*) > 1;

16. Compare this month vs last month sales

```sql id="q16"
SELECT month, sales,
       LAG(sales) OVER (ORDER BY month)
FROM MonthlySales;

17. Top 3 products by revenue

```sql id="q17"
SELECT p.product_name,
       SUM(s.amount) AS revenue
FROM Products p
JOIN Sales s
ON p.product_id = s.product_id
GROUP BY p.product_name
ORDER BY revenue DESC
LIMIT 3;

18. City with highest customers

```sql id="q18"
SELECT city, COUNT(*) AS total
FROM Customers
GROUP BY city
ORDER BY total DESC
LIMIT 1;

19. Customers with more than 5 orders

```sql id="q19"
SELECT customer_id,
       COUNT(*) AS order_count
FROM Orders
GROUP BY customer_id
HAVING COUNT(*) > 5;

20. Inactive customers (last 6 months)

```sql id="q20"
SELECT c.customer_name,
       MAX(o.order_date)
FROM Customers c
LEFT JOIN Orders o
ON c.customer_id = o.customer_id
GROUP BY c.customer_id, c.customer_name
HAVING MAX(o.order_date) < DATE_SUB(CURDATE(), INTERVAL 6 MONTH);

Takeaway :

Understood how to use JOINs to combine multiple tables
Learned proper use of GROUP BY and HAVING
Improved knowledge of aggregate functions like SUM, COUNT, MAX, AVG
Learned how to handle NULL values in queries
Practiced date functions like CURDATE and DATE_SUB
Understood how window functions like LAG work
Improved ability to solve real-world SQL problems step by step
Gained confidence in writing interview-level SQL queries
